==English==

===Etymology===
''Household management'', from {{L.}} '''[[oeconomia]]''', from [[w:Greek language|Greek]] '''[[oikonomia]]''' ''household management'' from '''[[oikonomos]]''' ''manager, steward'', from '''[[oikos]]''' ''house'' (cognate with Latin '''[[vicus]]''' ''district'', '''[[vicinus]]''' ''near''; [[w:Old English|Old English]] '''[[wic]]''' ''dwelling, village''; see ''[[villa]]'') + '''[[nomos]]''' ''managing'' from '''[[nemein]]''' ''manage'' (see ''[[numismatics]]''). The sense of ''manage the resources of a country'' (short for political economy) is from 1651. Hence, economic (1835) means ''related to the science of economics'', while [[economical]] (1780) retains the sense ''characterized by thrift''.

